        {
          "renderType": "container",
          "maxWidth": "xs",
          "richTextStyles": true,
          "content": [
            {
              "renderType": "rich-text",
              "tag": "h3",
              "content": "Development"
            },
            {
              "renderType": "rich-text",
              "tag": "p",
              "content": "I was initially tasked with leading only visual design but with some changes in the team also led the development effort. One of the first tasks was figuring out how to incorporate animation in a performant and accessible way that would also complement the goals of the site. One of the main goals of the site was to surpass the physical exhibit and enhance the storytelling element. We decided that subtle fade/reveal animations on scroll would be a great way to achieve this. The site would unfurl before site visitors and guide them through the content in a smooth and elegant way. One example is the quote in the hero section of the homepage fading in line by line."
            },
            {
              "renderType": "rich-text",
              "tag": "p",
              "content": "In order to make this performant and accessible we made use of the Intersection Observer API and reduce motion media query. Intersection Observer was perfect for determining if an element was visible in the viewport to trigger animations. We were also careful to leave animation to mainly cheap properties like transform and opacity to ensure a smooth experience. Accessibility was also important as animations can create a negative experience for users with motion sensitivities. We made use of the reduce motion query to remove transitions and animations for users with reduced motion set in their system preferences. We also luckily passed all accessibility scans conducted by the NMAI in time for launch, but did have to make some adjustments to ensure interactive elements, in particular, functioned well on screen readers too."
            }
          ]
